# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: edward-g-budd
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:edward-g-budd/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen graduated from Thomas Jefferson High School in San Antonio, Texas.
[src:edward-g-budd/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He received a Bachelor of Science degree from Texas A&M University in 1952, a Master of Science degree from Stevens Institute of Technology in 1958, and an honorary doctorate from Stevens in 1982.
[src:edward-g-budd/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen joined NASA in 1962 and served in key leadership roles critical to the success of the flights and lunar landings of the Apollo Program.
[src:edward-g-budd/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] From 1969 to 1972, Cohen was the manager for the Apollo Command and Service Modules.
[src:edward-g-budd/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He oversaw the design, development, production and test flights of the Space Shuttles as manager of NASA's Space Shuttle Orbiter Project Office from 1972 to 1982.
[src:edward-g-budd/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After serving as Director of Engineering at Johnson for several years, he was named director of the center in 1986, serving in that post until 1993.
[src:edward-g-budd/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After his retirement from NASA, Cohen taught mechanical engineering design at Texas A&M University.
[src:edward-g-budd/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] In 2000, he was appointed Professor Emeritus, and in 2010, he was awarded an honorary Doctor of Letters.
[src:edward-g-budd/alan-howard-engineer] Howard was born in Washington, D.C., in 1905.
[src:edward-g-budd/alan-howard-engineer] He obtained his BSc in electrical engineering from Purdue University in 1927.
[src:edward-g-budd/alan-howard-engineer] After his graduation in 1927, Howard started his lifelong career at the General Electric Company in Schenectady, New York as electrical engineer.
[src:edward-g-budd/alan-howard-engineer] He advanced rapidly various positions, and moved into steam turbine activities in 1941.
[src:edward-g-budd/alan-howard-engineer] In World War II at General Electric, Howard managed the development of aircraft gas turbine engine for the United States Air Force, and developed the TG 100 and TG 180 turboprop engine.
[src:edward-g-budd/alan-howard-engineer] Coffin Award by General Electric for his "accomplishments in connection with the design and development of the TG100 and TG180 aircraft gas turbines." In 1954, he was awarded the honorary degree of doctor of engineering by Purdue University.
[src:edward-g-budd/alan-howard-engineer] In 1962, he had been elected Fellow of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, and in 1964, he was awarded the ASME Medal.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Albert Kingsbury was born in Morris, Illinois and graduated from Cuyahoga Falls High School, OH in 1880.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] In addition to his interest in tribology and bearings, Kingsbury enjoyed the world of arts, history, and letters.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] He devoted much time to the study of foreign languages.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury died in Greenwich, Connecticut 1943, and is buried at the Green-Wood Cemetery, Brooklyn, New York.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] In 1884, Kingsbury attended the University of Akron to study Scientific-Latin courses.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] He dropped out and worked as a machine apprentice in Cuyahoga Falls.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury credited this as an important experience that led him to advance his career in engineering.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury resumed his formal education at Ohio State University, but he again dropped out to work as a machinist with the Warner and Swasey Company in Cleveland.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury received his mechanical engineering degree from Cornell University in 1887.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] It was at Cornell that he met Professor Robert Henry Thurston.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Professor Thurston was instrumental in shaping Kingsbury's interest in bearings and tribology.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Working under Professor Thurston, Kingsbury conducted tests on bearing materials for the Pennsylvania Railroad.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] His craftsmanship, honed by his experience in machine shops, allowed Kingsbury to fit half-bushings to the journal by scraping.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] His hand fitting produced the small tolerances that promoted film lubrication.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] These bearings, when ran showed no measurable signs of wear, and was Kingsbury's prompt to the creation of the thrust bearings which now bear his name.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury pursued a teaching position at the University of New Hampshire.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Within two years, he was a professor of Mechanical Engineering courses at the university.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] His new position at the university allowed him to continue pursuing his interest in lubrication.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] During his time at the University of New Hampshire, he created an innovative test machine to measure friction in coarse pitch, lubricated screw threads at loads of up to 14,000 psi.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] The usefulness of this invention received mixed reviews from the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME).
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] His research also covered fluid lubricated bearings, and he published a paper entitled "Experiments with an Air Lubricated Bearing".
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] It was at this university that he envisioned the Kingsbury thrust bearing.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury joined the Worcester Polytechnic Institute to continue pursuing his interest in lubrication.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] He secured expansions for laboratory facilities and funding to continue his tests on a centrally pivoted thrust bearing with the aid of his students.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury's research at the University of New Hampshire led him to conceive an early Kingsbury bearing that consisted of several stationary arc segments facing a thrust collar on the rotating shaft.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Each segment would have a boss on the side away from the thrust collar, allowing it to tilt and form an oil wedge that would carry the thrust.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury tested this new bearing with a modified version of his earlier screw thread testing machine.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] The bearing was successful with pressures of up to 4,000 psi at speeds of 285 rpm.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] This pressure exceeded that for common collar-type bearings by a factor of 80 to 100, thus proving the promise of the Kingsbury bearing.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury joined the Westinghouse Electric Company in Pittsburgh as a general engineer.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] He used this as an opportunity to advance the development of his thrust bearings in an industrial setting.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Unfortunately, the first test of his thrust bearing was a failure.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] His bearing overheated during the test and was discarded.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] This made the company skeptical of Kingsbury's invention, but Westinghouse's skepticism did not dent Kingsbury's enthusiasm.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury would later fund his own test that proved his bearings successful.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Unfortunately, Westinghouse decided to stick to more conventional ball bearings for their motors.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury tried to file for a U.S. patent during 1907.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] His initial application was rejected as a British patent had been granted in 1905 to A.G.M.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury was able to demonstrate that his 1898 test at the University of New Hampshire predated Michell's work, so in 1910 Kingsbury was awarded US patent No.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] 947242 for the tilting pad thrust bearing.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury would eventually run his own business with the Westinghouse Machine Co. building his bearings.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] This allowed him to actively pursue applications for his newly patented thrust bearing.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] His first chance came when the Pennsylvania Water and Power Co. gave him the opportunity to demonstrate his bearing on their power generator at the Susquehanna River.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] His first bearing was a failure as it was immediately destroyed by Hillson wiping.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Fortunately for Kingsbury, the Pennsylvania Water and Power Co. gave him a second chance.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] His bearing succeeded this time, and worked flawlessly for the next 25 years.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] When it was inspected after 25 years, there was so little evidence of wear that it was calculated that the bearing would last 1,300 to 1,700 years.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] The same bearing is still operating smoothly today.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] In 1921, the Kingsbury thrust bearing had become so popular that Westinghouse could no longer keep up with the demand, thus prompting Kingsbury to set up his own manufacturing plant.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury continued to pursue his interest in bearings and tribology later in his life.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] One of his greatest achievements was his analysis of the effects of side leakage of lubricants from bearings.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] By recognizing the analogy in the equations for lubrication and those for electrical flow in a conductive fluid and variable depth, Kingsbury was able to make complicated predictions of slider load capacity well before the advent of computers.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury made important contributions to the area of boundary lubrication.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] He was the first to recognize that some fluid lubricants possess a friction-reducing property that is independent of viscosity, which he called 'oiliness'.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] His findings were of great significance since they demonstrated that the hydrodynamic theory of lubrication did not describe completely the lubricating mechanism of fluids.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Later work by Hardy and Doubleday showed that this property was related to the ability of polar lubricants to adsorb and form close-packed monolayers on the sliding surfaces.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] for his wide-ranging contributions to the field, Kingsbury was named as one of the 23 "Men of Tribology" by Duncan Dowson.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury received many accolades for his contributions to science and engineering.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] He was awarded the Gold Medal of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers in 1931; the Elliott Cresson Medal of the Franklin Institute; and honorary doctorates from the University of New Hampshire and Worcester Polytechnic Institute.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] He was elected Honorary Member of ASME in 1940.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] The Kingsbury Hall at the University of New Hampshire also pays homage to the great inventor.
[src:edward-g-budd/albert-kingsbury] Albert Kingsbury was inducted into the National Inventors Hall of Fame.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] Swasey was born near Exeter, New Hampshire to Nathaniel and Abigail Swasey.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] He apprenticed as a machinist at the Exeter Machine Works and was afterwards employed at Pratt & Whitney.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] As his career progressed, he became a foreman in the gear-cutting section.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] He developed a new technique for making gear-tooth cutters.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] In 1880, he and Warner formed their eponymous firm, which quickly moved to Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] Swasey would perform the engineering and machine development at this company.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] The close friends Warner and Swasey built their homes next to each other on Euclid Avenue in Cleveland, a street that was known as "Millionaire's Row".
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] In addition to army ordnance contracts, the firm of Warner & Swasey became notable for their work on astronomical observatories and equipment.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] The founders were interested in astronomy as an avocation, and in the field's quest for better optical telescopes, which was burgeoning at the time.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] They also realized that obtaining contracts to build large astronomical observatories would provide publicity for their company.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] In 1885, Swasey completed work at McCormick Observatory on the 45-foot dome, which was the largest in the world, and had a unique, 3 shutter design.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] In 1887, Swasey built the mount for the 36-inch refracting telescope at Lick Observatory.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] In 1898, he manufactured a dividing engine for the U.S.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] Naval Observatory that was used to make the meridian circles.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] Both the building and dome of the Dominion Astrophysical Observatory were made by Warner and Swasey Co.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] Other observatory telescopes and components were built by the company at the Kenwood Observatory, Yerkes Observatory, Argentine National Observatory, the Swasey Observatory at Denison University, and the Case School of Applied Science Observatory.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] From 1904 until 1905, he was the president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] Both Warner and Swasey were amateur astronomers.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] When they became trustees of the Case School of Applied Science, they donated to the school their private observatory, which they had built between their neighboring houses in East Cleveland.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] Relocated to a new building, this became the Warner and Swasey Observatory.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] The observatory maintained by the department today is still known by this name today.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] Swasey Hall (1917, "懷士堂"), a red brick hall, is the landmark of Sun Yat-sen University, one of the top colleges in China.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] It was named after Swasey for his USD$25000 donation to the then university Christian YMCA society hall.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] The chimes in the chapel were included as a memorial to his wife, Lavinia Marston Swasey.
[src:edward-g-budd/ambrose-swasey] The Warner & Swasey Company he cofounded would continue until 1980, when it was acquired by Bendix Corporation.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] The **American Aeronautical Corporation** (AAC) was founded in October 1928 by Enea Bossi, located at 730 Fifth Avenue in Port Washington, New York.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] Its purpose was to build Savoia-Marchetti seaplanes under license.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] Licenses were acquired for both the S-55 and the S-56 and both were tested at Miller Army Air Field, but only the latter made it to production.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] The S-56 was first introduced in Italy two years earlier as a three-seat amphibious aircraft powered by air-cooled radial engines in the 90- to 110 horsepower (82 kW) range.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] The AAC fitted it with an American Kinner engine.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] The size and price of the vehicle appealed to recreational aviators, despite its difficult handling.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] On water, the plane lacked a rudder; on ground, the plane only had a non-steerable tail skid (that is: no conventional brakes); and in the air, when the wheels were extended, the added drag complicated the steering.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] Thirty-six S-56s were built under ATC A-287, which was awarded on 4 January 1930.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] The S-56 became the first plane used by the New York City Police Department, which used it to enforce flying regulations, assist with sea rescues, and to chase rum-runners during the Prohibition era.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] A follow-up design, the S-56B, proved even more successful.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] ATC A-336, for the S-56B design, was awarded on 11 July 1930.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] The S-56B included a more powerful 125 horsepower (93 kW) Kinner B-5 engine and sold for $7,825.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] Whereas the prices for the S-56 and S-56B were modest for the time, the Great Depression caused sales to drop significantly by 1933.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] In December 1928, the AAC named Captain Hugo (Ugo) Veniero d'Annunzio, son of Gabriele d'Annunzio, as a director and vice president.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] Captain d'Annunzio had never arrived in the United States in 1917 to supervise the manufacture of Caproni bombing planes at the Fisher Body plant, as an agent of Isotta Fraschini.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] With a factory already in place in Port Washington, on Long Island, the AAC sponsored the construction of a seaplane base in the town.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] It was officially dedicated by the striking of a bronze medal on 14 September 1929.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] Prominent speakers at the dedication included Edward P.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] In 1933, the American Aeronautical Corporation facility was purchased by Pan Am and became the base for early survey flights for transatlantic air service.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] In 1937, the first regular commercial transatlantic airline service in America started from the facility.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-aeronautical-corporation] International seaplane flights continued into the early 1940s.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The **American Federation of Labor** (**A.F. of L.**) was a national federation of labor unions in the United States that continues today as the AFL-CIO.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] It was founded in Columbus, Ohio, in 1886 by an alliance of craft unions eager to provide mutual support and disappointed in the Knights of Labor.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Samuel Gompers was elected the full-time president at its founding convention and was re-elected every year except one until his death in 1924.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] He became the major spokesperson for the union movement.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. was the largest union grouping, even after the creation of the Congress of Industrial Organizations (CIO) by unions that were expelled by the A.F. of L. in 1935.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. was founded and dominated by craft unions, especially in the building trades.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In the late 1930s, craft affiliates expanded by organizing on an industrial union basis to meet the challenge from the CIO.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. and the CIO competed bitterly in the late 1930s but then cooperated during World War II and afterward.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1955, the two merged to create the AFL-CIO, which has comprised the longest lasting and most influential labor federation in the United States to this day.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The American Federation of Labor (A.F. of L.) was organized as an association of trade unions in 1886.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The Federation of Organized Trades and Labor Unions also merged into what would become the American Federation of Labor.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] One of the organizations embroiled in this controversy was the Cigar Makers' International Union (CMIU), a group subject to competition from a dual union, a rival "Progressive Cigarmakers' Union", organized by members suspended or expelled by the CMIU.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The two cigar unions competed with one another in signing contracts with various cigar manufacturers, who were at this same time combining themselves into manufacturers' associations of their own in New York City, Detroit, Cincinnati, Chicago, and Milwaukee.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In January 1886, the Cigar Manufacturers' Association of New York City announced a 20 percent wage cut in factories around the city.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The Cigar Makers' International Union refused to accept the cut and 6,000 of its members in 19 factories were locked out by the owners.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Just when it appeared that the strike might be won, the New York District Assembly of the Knights of Labor leaped into the breach, offering to settle with the 19 factories at a lower wage scale than that proposed by the CMIU, so long as only the Progressive Cigarmakers' Union was employed.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The leadership of the CMIU was enraged and demanded that the New York District Assembly be investigated and punished by the national officials of the Knights of Labor.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The committee of investigation was controlled by individuals friendly to the New York District Assembly, however, and the latter was exonerated.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The American Federation of Labor was thus originally formed as an alliance of craft unions outside the Knights of Labor as a means of defending themselves against this and similar incursions.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] On April 25, 1886, a circular letter was issued by Adolph Strasser of the Cigar Makers and P.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] McGuire of the Carpenters, addressed to all national trade unions and calling for their attendance of a conference in Philadelphia on May 18.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Forty-three invitations were mailed, which drew the attendance of 20 delegates and letters of approval from 12 other unions.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] For its part, the Knights of Labor considered the demand for the parcelling of the labor movement into narrow craft-based fiefdoms to be anathema, a violation of the principle of solidarity of all workers across craft lines.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Negotiations with the dissident craft unions were nipped in the bud by the governing General Assembly of the K of L, however, with the organization's Grand Master Workman, Terence V.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Powderly refusing to enter into serious discussions on the matter.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The actions of the New York District Assembly of the K of L were upheld.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Revenue for the new organization was to be raised on the basis of a "per-capita tax" of its member organizations, set at the rate of one-half cent per member per month (i.e. six cents per year, equal to $2.15 today).
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Governance of the organization was to be by annual conventions, with one delegate allocated for every 4,000 members of each affiliated union.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The founding convention voted to make the President of the new federation a full-time official at a salary of $1,000 per year (equal to $35,833 today), and Samuel Gompers of the Cigar Makers' International Union was elected to the position.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Gompers would ultimately be re-elected to the position by annual conventions of the organization for every year save one until his death nearly four decades later.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Although the founding convention of the A.F. of L. had authorized the establishment of a publication for the new organization, Gompers made use of the existing labor press to generate support for the position of the craft unions against the Knights of Labor.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Headway was made in the form of endorsement by various local labor bodies.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Some assemblies of the K of L supported the Cigar Makers' position and departed the organization: in Baltimore, 30 locals left the organization, while the membership of the Knights in Chicago fell from 25,000 in 1886 to just 3,500 in 1887.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Factional warfare broke out in the K of L, with Terence Powderly blaming the organization's travails on "radicals" in its ranks, while those opposing Powderly called for an end to what they perceived as "autocratic leadership".
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In the face of the steady disintegration of its rival, the fledgling American Federation of Labor struggled to maintain itself, with the group showing very slow and incremental growth in its first years, only cracking the 250,000 member mark in 1892.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The group from the outset concentrated upon the income and working conditions of its membership as its almost sole focus.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] This fundamentally conservative "pure and simple" approach limited the A.F. of L. to matters pertaining to working conditions and rates of pay, relegating political goals to its allies in the political sphere.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The Federation favored pursuit of workers' immediate demands rather than challenging the property rights of owners, and took a pragmatic view of politics which favored tactical support for particular politicians over formation of a party devoted to workers' interests.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L.'s leadership believed the expansion of the capitalist system was seen as the path to betterment of labor, an orientation making it possible for the A.F. of L. to present itself as what one historian has called "the conservative alternative to working class radicalism".
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. faced its first major reversal when employers launched an open shop movement in 1903, designed to drive unions out of construction, mining, longshore and other industries.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Membership in the A.F. of L.'s affiliated unions declined between 1904 and 1914 in the face of this concerted anti-union drive, which made effective use of legal injunctions against strikes, court rulings given force when backed with the armed might of the state.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] At its November 1907 Convention in Norfolk, Virginia, the A.F. of L. founded the future North America's Building Trades Unions (NABTU) as its Department of Building Trades.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Ever the pragmatist, Gompers argued that labor should "reward its friends and punish its enemies" in both major parties.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] However, in the 1900s (decade), the two parties began to realign, with the main faction of the Republican Party coming to identify with the interests of banks and manufacturers, while a substantial portion of the rival Democratic Party took a more labor-friendly position.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] While not precluding its members from belonging to the Socialist Party or working with its members, the A.F. of L. traditionally refused to pursue the tactic of independent political action by the workers in the form of the existing Socialist Party or the establishment of a new labor party.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] After 1908, the organization's tie to the Democratic party grew increasingly strong.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Some unions within the A.F. of L. helped form and participated in the National Civic Federation.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The National Civic Federation was formed by several progressive employers who sought to avoid labor disputes by fostering collective bargaining and "responsible" unionism.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Major Republican leaders, such as President William McKinley and Senator Mark Hanna, made pro-labor statements.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Labor's participation in the National Civic Federation created internal division within the A.F. of L.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The Socialist element who believed the only way to help workers was to remove large industry from private ownership, denounced labor's efforts at cooperation with the capitalists.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. nonetheless continued its association with the group, which declined in importance as the decade of the 1910s drew to a close.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] By the 1890s, Gompers was planning an international federation of labor, starting with the expansion of A.F. of L. affiliates in Canada, especially Ontario.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] He helped the Canadian Trades and Labour Congress with money and organizers, and by 1902, the A.F. of L. came to dominate the Canadian union movement.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. vigorously opposed unrestricted immigration from Europe for moral, cultural, and racial reasons.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The issue unified the workers who feared that an influx of new workers would flood the labor market and lower wages.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Nativism was not a factor because upwards of half the union members were themselves immigrants or the sons of immigrants from Ireland, Germany and Britain.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Nativism was a factor when the A.F. of L. even more strenuously opposed all immigration from Asia because it represented (to its Euro-American members) an alien culture that could not be assimilated into American society.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. intensified its opposition after 1906 and was instrumental in passing immigration restriction bills from the 1890s to the 1920s, such as the 1921 Emergency Quota Act and the Immigration Act of 1924, and seeing that they were strictly enforced.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Mink (1986) concludes that the link between the A.F. of L. and the Democratic Party rested in part on immigration issues, noting the large corporations, which supported the Republicans, wanted more immigration to augment their labor force.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Prohibition gained strength as the German American community came under fire.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. was against prohibition as it was viewed as cultural right of the working class to drink.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Child labor was an issue on which the A.F. of L. found common ground with middle class reformers who otherwise kept their distance.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. joined campaigns at the state and national level to limit the employment of children under age 14.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1904 a major national organization emerged, the National Child Labor Committee (NCLC).
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In state after state reformers launched crusades to pass laws restricting child labor, with the ultimate goals of rescuing young bodies and increasing school attendance.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The frustrations included the Supreme Court striking down two national laws as unconstitutional, and weak enforcement of state laws due to the political influence of employers.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. and its affiliates were strong supporters of the war effort.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The risk of disruptions to war production by labor radicals provided the A.F. of L. political leverage to gain recognition and mediation of labor disputes, often in favor of improvements for workers.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. unions avoided strikes in favor of arbitration.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Wages soared as near-full employment was reached at the height of the war.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. unions strongly encouraged young men to enlist in the military, and fiercely opposed efforts to reduce recruiting and slow war production by pacifists, the anti-war Industrial Workers of the World (IWW) and the radical faction of Socialists.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] To keep factories running smoothly, President Wilson established the National War Labor Board in 1918, which forced management to negotiate with existing unions.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Wilson also appointed A.F. of L. president Gompers to the powerful Council of National Defense, where he set up the War Committee on Labor.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] F. of L. was strongly committed to the national war aims and cooperated closely with Washington.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] It used the opportunity to grow rapidly.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Gompers chaired the wartime Labor Advisory Board.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] He attended the Paris Peace Conference in 1919 as an official advisor on labor issues.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1920, the A.F. of L. petitioned Washington for the release of prisoners who had been convicted under Wartime Emergency Laws.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Wilson did not act but President Warren Harding did so.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] While 1919 was the first year of peace after the end of the First World War, it was a year of great turmoil in the US labor movement.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] A.F. of L. membership soared to 2.4 million in 1917 and 4.1 million at the end of 1919.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. unions tried to make their gains permanent and called a series of major strikes in meat, steel, and other industries.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] This was coupled with the First Red Scare, which feared a workers' revolution in the image of the Russian Revolution in the US.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] While the Red Scare centered its attacks on more radical unions, such as the IWW, the AFL was also subject to repression from both the government and various vigilante groups such as the American Legion.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] 1919 was also a decisive year in the AFL's tumultuous relationship to the ever-growing population of black industrial workers, a result of the Great Migration.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Due to jobs being taken away from soldiers fighting in Europe and given, largely, to black workers new to the Northern states, many returning white soldiers laid the blame for their economic uncertainty on the black workers.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] This caused increased racial tension across the country, which, when coupled with the nationalism stoked by the war, led to the Red Summer, a series of outbreaks of mass racial violence that not only targeted black people in general but also organized workers broadly.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The AFL did little to aid the black workers trying to hold on to a peaceful existence in the north and did less to protest the increasingly cruel treatment of black workers in the Deep South made painful apparent by the Elaine Massacre.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The failure of the AFL to deal with the Red Scare, racial issues, and generally capitalize on the momentum of the militant organizing that dominated the year 1919 after the Seattle General Strike led to a decline in the organization's prestige and respect among workers.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] This left them open to being ravaged by open shop drives which intensified in the wake of 1919.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In the pro-business environment of the 1920s, business launched a large-scale offensive on behalf of the so-called "open shop", which meant that a person did not have to be a union member to be hired.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] A.F. of L. unions lost membership steadily until 1933.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1924, following the death of Samuel Gompers, UMWA member and A.F. of L. vice president William Green became the president of the labor federation.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The organization endorsed pro-labor Progressive candidate Robert M.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] La Follette in the 1924 presidential election.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] He only carried his home state of Wisconsin.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The campaign failed to establish a permanent independent party closely connected to the labor movement, however, and thereafter the Federation embraced ever more closely the Democratic Party, despite the fact that many union leaders remained Republicans.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Herbert Hoover in 1928 won the votes of many Protestant A.F. of L. members.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The Great Depression were hard times for the unions, and membership fell sharply across the country.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] As the national economy began to recover in 1933, so did union membership.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Roosevelt, a Democrat, strongly favored labor unions.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] He made sure that relief operations like the Civilian Conservation Corps did not include a training component that would produce skilled workers who would compete with union members in a still glutted market.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The major legislation was the National Labor Relations Act of 1935, called the Wagner Act.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] It greatly strengthened organized unions, especially by weakening the company unions that many workers belonged to.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] It was to the members advantage to transform a company union into a local of an A.F. of L. union, and thousands did so, dramatically boosting the membership.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The Wagner Act also set up to the National Labor Relations Board, which used its powers to rule in favor of unions and against the companies.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In the early 1930s, A.F. of L. president William Green (president, 1924–1952) experimented with an industrial approach to organizing in the automobile and steel industries.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. made forays into industrial unionism by chartering federal labor unions, which would organize across an industry and be chartered by the Federation, not through existing craft unions, guilds, or brotherhoods.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] As early as 1923, the A.F. of L. had chartered federal labor unions, including six news writer locals that had formerly been part of the International Typographical Union.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] However, in the 1930s the A.F. of L. began chartering these federal labor unions as an industrial organizing strategy.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The dues in these federal labor unions (FLUs) were kept intentionally low to make them more accessible to low paid industrial workers; however, these low dues later allowed the Internationals in the Federation to deny members of FLUs voting membership at conventions.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1933, Green sent William Collins to Detroit to organize automobile workers into a federal labor union.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] That same year workers at the Westinghouse plant in East Springfield MA, members of federal labor union 18476, struck for recognition.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1933, the A.F. of L. received 1,205 applications for charters for federal labor unions, 1006 of which were granted.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] By 1934, the A.F. of L. had successfully organized 32,500 autoworkers using the federal labor union model.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Most of the leadership of the craft union internationals that made up the federation, advocated for the FLU's to be absorbed into existing craft union internationals and for these internationals to have supremacy of jurisdiction.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1934, one hundred FLUs met separately and demanded that the A.F. of L. continue to issue charters to unions organizing on an industrial basis independent of the existing craft union internationals.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1935 the FLUs representing autoworkers and rubber workers both held conventions independent of the craft union internationals.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] By the 1935 A.F. of L. convention, Green and the advocates of traditional craft unionism faced increasing dissension led by John L.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Lewis of the coal miners, Sidney Hillman of the Amalgamated, David Dubinsky of the Garment Workers, Charles Howard of the ITU, Thomas McMahon of the Textile Workers, and Max Zaritsky of the Hat, Cap, and Millinery Workers, in addition to the members of the FLU's themselves.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Lewis argued that the A.F.of L. was too heavily oriented toward traditional craftsmen, and was overlooking the opportunity to organize millions of semiskilled workers, especially those in industrial factories that made automobiles, rubber, glass and steel.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1935 Lewis led the dissenting unions in forming a new Congress for Industrial Organization (CIO) within the A.F. of L.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Both the new CIO industrial unions, and the older A.F. of L. crafts unions grew rapidly after 1935.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] He won reelection in a landslide in 1936, and by a closer margin in 1940.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Labor unions gave strong support in 1940, compared to very strong support in 1936.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The Gallup Poll showed CIO voters declined from 85% in 1935 to 79% in 1940.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Other union members went from 74% to 57%.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Blue collar workers who were not union members went 72% to 64%.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. retained close ties to the Democratic machines in big cities through the 1940s.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Its membership surged during the war and it held on to most of its new members after wartime legal support for labor was removed.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Despite its close connections to many in Congress, the A.F. of L. was not able to block the Taft–Hartley Act in 1947.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Also in 1947, the union supported the strike efforts of thousands of switchboard operators by donating thousands of dollars.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1955, the A.F. of L. and CIO merged to form the AFL-CIO, headed by George Meany.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] During its first years, the A.F. of L. admitted nearly anyone.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Gompers opened the A.F. of L. to radical and socialist workers and to some semiskilled and unskilled workers.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Women, African Americans, and immigrants joined in small numbers.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] By the 1890s, the Federation had begun to organize only skilled workers in craft unions and became an organization of mostly white men.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Although the A.F. of L. preached a policy of egalitarianism in regard to African-American workers, it actively discriminated against them.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. sanctioned the maintenance of segregated locals within its affiliates, particularly in the construction and railroad industries, a practice that often excluded black workers altogether from union membership and thus from employment in organized industries.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] These practices led prominent labor historian Philip S.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1901, the A.F. of L. lobbied Congress to reauthorize the 1882 Chinese Exclusion Act, and issued a pamphlet entitled "Some reasons for Chinese Exclusion.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] American Manhood against Asiatic Coolieism.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. also began one of the first organized labor boycotts when they began putting white stickers on the cigars made by unionized white cigar rollers while simultaneously discouraging consumers from purchasing cigars rolled by Chinese workers.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In general, AFL unions preferred native-born workers, discouraged the speaking of any language other than English by its members, and had strict citizenship requirements of the immigrants it did admit to the union for the majority of its history.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In most ways, the A.F. of L.'s treatment of women workers paralleled its policy towards black workers.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. never adopted a strict policy of gender exclusion and, at times, even came out in favor of women's unionism.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] However, despite such rhetoric, it only half-heartedly supported women's attempts to organize and, more often, took pains to keep women out of unions and the workforce altogether.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Only two national unions affiliated with the A.F. of L. at its founding openly included women, and others passed bylaws barring women's membership entirely.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. hired its first female organizer, Mary Kenney O'Sullivan, only in 1892, released her after five months, and it did not replace her or hire another woman national organizer until 1908.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Women who organized their own unions were often turned down in bids to join the Federation, and even women who did join unions found them hostile or intentionally inaccessible.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Unions often held meetings at night or in bars when women might find it difficult to attend and where they might feel uncomfortable, and male unionists heckled women who tried to speak at meetings.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Generally, the A.F. of L. viewed women workers as competition, strikebreakers, or an unskilled labor reserve that kept wages low.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] As such, it often opposed women's employment entirely.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] When it organized women workers, it most often did so to protect men's jobs and earning power, not to improve the conditions, lives, or wages of women workers.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In response, most women workers remained outside the labor movement.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1900, only 3.3% of working women were organized into unions.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1910, even as the A.F. of L. surged forward in membership, that number had dipped to 1.5%.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] It improved to 6.6% over the next decade, but women remained mostly outside of unions and practically invisible inside of them into the mid-1920s.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Attitudes gradually changed within the A.F. of L. by the pressure of organized female workers.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Female-domination began to emerge in the first two decades of the 20th century, including particularly the International Ladies Garment Workers' Union.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Women organized independent locals among New York hat makers, in the Chicago stockyards, and among Jewish and Italian waist makers, to name only three examples.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Through the efforts of middle-class reformers and activists, often of the Women's Trade Union League, those unions joined the A.F. of L.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In some cases, the A.F. of L. mediated the dispute, usually by favoring the larger or more influential union.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. often reversed its jurisdictional rulings over time, as the continuing jurisdictional battles between the Brewers and the Teamsters showed.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Affiliates within the AFL formed "departments" to help resolve these jurisdictional conflicts and to provide a more effective voice for member unions in given industries.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The Metal Trades Department engaged in some organizing of its own, primarily in shipbuilding, where unions such as the Pipefitters, Machinists and Iron Workers joined through local metal workers' councils to represent a diverse group of workers.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The Railway Employes' Department dealt with both jurisdictional disputes between affiliates and pursued a common legislative agenda for all of them.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. made efforts in its early years to assist its affiliates in organizing: it advanced funds or provided organizers or, in some cases, such as the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, the Teamsters and the American Federation of Musicians, helped form the union.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. also chartered "federal unions", local unions not affiliated with any international union, in those fields in which no affiliate claimed jurisdiction.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. also encouraged the formation of local labor bodies, known as central labor councils, in major metropolitan areas in which all of the affiliates could participate.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Those local labor councils acquired a great deal of influence in some cases.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] For example, the Chicago Federation of Labor spearheaded efforts to organize packinghouse and steel workers during and immediately after World War I.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Local building trades councils also became powerful in some areas.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In San Francisco, the local Building Trades Council, led by Carpenters official P.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] McCarthy, not only dominated the local labor council but helped elect McCarthy mayor of San Francisco in 1909.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In a very few cases early in the A.F. of L.'s history, state and local bodies defied A.F. of L. policy or chose to disaffiliate over policy disputes.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Though Gompers had contact with socialists and such as A.F. of L. co-founder Peter J.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] McGuire, the A.F. of L. adopted a philosophy of "business unionism" that emphasized unions' contribution to businesses' profits and national economic growth.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The business unionist approach also focused on skilled workers' immediate job-related interests, while refusing to "rush to the support of any one of the numerous society-saving or society destroying schemes" involved in larger political issues.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] This approach was set by Gompers, who was influenced by a fellow cigar maker (and former socialist) Ferdinand Laurrel.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Despite his socialist contacts, Gompers himself was not a socialist.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Employers discovered the efficacy of labor injunctions, first used with great effect by the Cleveland administration during the Pullman Strike in 1894.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. thought that it had achieved the latter with the passage of the Clayton Antitrust Act in 1914—which Gompers referred to as "Labor's Magna Carta".
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] 443 (1921), the United States Supreme Court narrowly read the Act and codified the federal courts' existing power to issue injunctions rather than limit it.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The court read the phrase "between an employer and employees" (contained in the first paragraph of the Act) to refer only to cases involving an employer and its own employees, leaving the courts free to punish unions for engaging in sympathy strikes or secondary boycotts.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L.'s pessimistic attitude towards politics did not, on the other hand, prevent affiliated unions from pursuing their own agendas.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Construction unions supported legislation that governed entry of contractors into the industry and protected workers' rights to pay, rail and mass production industries sought workplace safety legislation, and unions generally agitated for the passage of workers' compensation statutes.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] At the same time, the A.F. of L. took efforts on behalf of women in supporting protective legislation.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] It advocated fewer hours for women workers, and based its arguments on assumptions of female weakness.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Like efforts to unionize, most support for protective legislation for women came out of a desire to protect men's jobs.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] If women's hours could be limited, reasoned A.F. of L. officials, they would infringe less on male employment and earning potential.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] But the A.F. of L. also took more selfless efforts.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Even from the 1890s, the A.F. of L. declared itself vigorously in favor of women's suffrage.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] It often printed pro-suffrage articles in its periodical, and in 1918, it supported the National Union of Women's Suffrage.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. relaxed its rigid stand against legislation after the death of Gompers.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Its proposals for unemployment benefits (made in the late 1920s) were too modest to have practical value, as the Great Depression soon showed.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The impetus for the major federal labor laws of the 1930s came from the New Deal.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The enormous growth in union membership came after Congress passed the National Industrial Recovery Act in 1933 and National Labor Relations Act in 1935.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The A.F. of L. refused to sanction or participate in the mass strikes led by John L.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] Lewis of the United Mine Workers and other left unions such as the Amalgamated Clothing Workers of America.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] After the A.F. of L. expelled the CIO in 1936, the CIO undertook a major organizing effort.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In 1947, when the Taft-Hartley Act was passed, political activities were stirred.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] In resistance to the new law, the CIO joined the A.F. of L., and political co-operation set the path for union unity.
[src:edward-g-budd/american-federation-of-labor-p01] The two groups merged, eight years later, into the AFL–CIO coalition with George Meany as the new president.
[src:edward-g-budd/asme-medal] The **ASME Medal**, created in 1920, is the highest award bestowed by the ASME (founded as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers) Board of Governors for "eminently distinguished engineering achievement".
[src:edward-g-budd/asme-medal] The award has been presented every year since 1996 (first medalist was awarded in 1921), and it consists of a $15,000 honorarium, a certificate, a travel supplement not to exceed $750, and a gold medal inscribed with the words, "What is not yet, may be".
[src:edward-g-budd/asme-medal] ASME also gives out a number of other awards yearly, including the Edwin F.
[src:edward-g-budd/asme-medal] Church Medal, the Holley medal, and the Soichiro Honda medal.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] In 1944, he received the American Society of Mechanical Engineers award for outstanding engineering achievements.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] He was posthumously admitted to the Automotive Hall of Fame and National Railroad Hall of Fame.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] Edward Gowen Budd was born in Smyrna, Delaware, on December 28, 1870.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] He showed interest at an early age in the mechanical trades.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] While working, he took courses at night in drafting and mechanical engineering at the Franklin Institute and the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] After graduating from public high school aged 17, Budd went to work as a machinist apprentice at Taylor Iron Works.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] In 1890, he moved to Philadelphia and worked as a machinist apprentice at Sellers Machines and Foundry Company.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] He left Sellers to accept a junior position with the Bement-Pond Tool Company.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] He moved up the ranks at Bement-Pond and became the department head for hydraulic press design.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] In 1898, he left Bement-Pond to worked at the American Pulley Company as chief draftsman.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] In 1898, he obtained a patent for a stamped steel pulley which was lighter and less expensive to produce.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] He patented his own design for a stamped steel pulley in 1900.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] In 1902, he joined Hale & Kilburn to bring his expertise in stamped steel construction to design railroad car furniture.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] He and fellow employee Morris Lachman implemented arc welding into the production process which allowed stamped steel to be put together in ways that were not previously possible.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] The lighter and more durable furniture became very successful.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] In 1904, he became the production manager of the plant and a member of the board of directors.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] In 1906, Hale & Kilburn partnered with the Pullman Company to design steel railroad cars that were only slightly heavier than wood cars, but less flammable and safer in a crash.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] Budd also worked on a partnership between Hale & Kilburn and the Hupp Motor Company to implement stamped and welded steel in the production of the Hupmobile, the first steel bodied car in the world.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] In 1911, Hale & Kilburn was purchased by J.P.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] Morgan who replaced much of the management with people that had less experience in metal manufacturing.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] Budd's ability to experiment and take on innovative but risky projects was limited by the new management.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] The stress of the new management affected his mental health.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] He took a two month leave of absence and resigned upon his return in 1912.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] On July 22, 1912, he founded the Edward G.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] Budd Manufacturing Company, with $75,000 of his own money and $25,000 in investments.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] He recruited talent from Hale & Kilburn and brought Joseph Ledwinka over to his new company.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] They began making bodies for metal trucks for a local coal company but soon expanded to making steel automobile bodies for Garford Motors and Oakland Motor Car Company, a division of General Motors.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] The business started to become successful and he was able to expand production with the purchase of the Grabowski Wagon Factory in Detroit to allow for production of steel parts closer to the final assembly location.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] He expanded his business with additional customers including Studebaker and Dodge.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] In 1914, Dodge placed an order for 5,000 steel automobile bodies and increased that order to 50,000 in 1915.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] He was known to conduct promotional stunts of rolling the cars down hills and having an elephant stand atop the vehicles to show the strength of steel bodied automobiles.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] He offered competitors of wood bodied cars the opportunity to replicate the challenges, but none took him up on it.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] In 1917, he founded the Budd Wheel Company to produce steel automobile wheels.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] During World War I, production of automobile bodies ceased and efforts were directed toward production of war effort materials including artillery carriage wheels, helmets, ordnance, and shell casings.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] Budd built the first all-steel sedan for Dodge in 1923.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] The Dodge brothers had not believed such a thing possible but they were persuaded to allow Budd to go ahead with the design, die-making and press-installation needed for actual production to begin.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] Other US manufacturers soon followed Dodge's lead.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] Closed bodies outsold open bodies from 1923 on.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] During the Great Depression in the 1930s, Budd pioneered the fabrication of stainless steel.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] The company partnered with American Aeronautical Corporation and implemented stainless steel in the construction of the Savoie Marchetti seaplane.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] He implemented stainless steel into the production of railroad cars and developed the shotweld process which allowed for thinner sheets of stainless steel to be combined without weakening the properties of the metal.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] He helped create the Pioneer Zephyr, a streamlined train for the Chicago, Burlington and Quincy Railroad.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] Budd stainless steel railway cars were very successful for many years.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] During World War II, Budd returned to manufacturing military equipment in his factories.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] He was the main maker of the bazooka rockets and the rifle grenade.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] His factories made artillery shells, aircraft components and a myriad of other military items.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] He partnered with the United States Navy to build the Budd RB Conestoga aircraft for military transport.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] He and his company were also instrumental in the development of the radial disk brake and the automatic wheel line.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] In 1933 and 1934, to prevent the American Federation of Labor from unionizing the Philadelphia operations, Budd fired over 1,000 workers who went on strike.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] He refused to re-hire the workers even after being ordered to by the National Labor Board.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] Budd died on November 30, 1946, at his home in the Germantown neighborhood of Philadelphia.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] He was interred at West Laurel Hill Cemetery in Bala Cynwyd, Pennsylvania.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] Budd's Pioneer Zephyr train is on permanent display at the Museum of Science and Industry in Chicago.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] His stainless steel prototype airplane, the Budd BB-1 Pioneer, is on display outside the Franklin Institute in Philadelphia.
[src:edward-g-budd/edward-g-budd] Budd was inducted into the Automotive Hall of Fame in 1985, and the National Railroad Hall of Fame in 2015.
